description: Bill Graham Presents This show is one for the history books and must be sampled if you haven't heard it. It's so OVER the top, but also right in the pocket, it floors me every time. I had no idea that Warren wanted Chuck Leavell to sit in that night (and it woulda been awesome!).  However, what I learned is that Zakk was playing is his own ABB cover band and knew all the tunes inside out so, he actually was a good choice - except for his tone and attitude. BUT! This is what makes it so much fun to listen to from a historical perspective. Give it a listen and let me know what y'all think (there is a link to the show in the article). I know Warren was lovin' it and Gregg was hatin' it...  "They were way fuckin’ cool, man. But it was hysterical, ’cause when we played “Dreams” I must have soloed for twenty minutes. I’d died and gone to heaven and I wasn’t going to stop. I was just jamming. But I almost gave [ABB drummer] Butch [Trucks] a coronary, ’cause every time we got to where the band was repeating the same lick, preparing to come out of the jam, I just keep soloing. I came over to Butch and he goes, “Zakk, fuck, man! Calm down a little bit, brother.” And I go, “But this is my favorite band.” And he goes, “Yeah, it’s mine, too, but just fuckin’ relax!” - Zakk Wylde Chuck Eitel Mark Rose Corrie Owens

Bill Graham Presents The artist of this piece Wes Wilson, has created what appears to be an Egyptian stylized portrait in a psychedelic sort of way. A woman's face surrounded by an unusual headdress is the central image on this "Poster From The Past". His signature style lettering besides her sets a good balance within the space of the poster. The director of graphics of the Oakland Museum was one of the first people in the professional art world to recognize the greatness of this kind of art. In ...  1967 she purchased the original artists drawing for the permanent collection of the Oakland Museum. She paid a whopping $250 dollars for it! VISION, is my only comment!  It was 51 (!!OMG!!) years ago on this day back in 1966 that Captain Beefheart and his Magic Band (misspelled on the poster), The Chocolate Watchband and The Great Pumpkin performed for three nights of Dance/Concerts at the Fillmore Auditorium here in San Francisco. This is BG Fillmore poster number #34 in the old series. It was printed two times.  Share this Egyptian Queen with a friend!  Royally Approved by  Professor Poster   See More
